## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified: Timeout enforcement** — thread is aborted when it exceeds a time limit.

### Why it breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is a no-op. The code will never cancel timed-out work.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(work, timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }

    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var workTask = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            return await workTask.WaitAsync(token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | `Task.Run` + `WaitAsync` abandons the task on timeout but the delegate keeps running on a thread-pool thread. Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cooperative cancellation cannot force-kill it. |
| **To truly stop work**, pass the token into `work` | Change the signature to `Func<CancellationToken, T>` and have the work check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular intervals. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed** | It allocates a timer internally when created with a timeout. Wrap in `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when` filter distinguishes timeout from external cancellation. |

### If `work` can cooperate (preferred)

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return await Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If `work` is uncooperative (can't modify it)

Move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout — this is the only way to truly force-terminate uncooperative code in modern .NET. The fire-and-forget `Task.Run` approach above will work for "best effort" scenarios where a leaked background thread is acceptable.

### Summary of API replacements

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---------------|--------|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(() => ..., token)` |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `await task.WaitAsync(token)` |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (cooperative) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested`, decide whether to continue |
